<font color="#FF0000">THE GOOD THE BAD &amp; THE UGLY</font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 17 21:12:11 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Paul <br>
Once again you have touched my heart and mind with well-chosen words that are full of heartfelt wisdom. You can make Marine jokes anytime you like, you've learned that right as well.<br><br>
Ed in his book “Scares and stripes Forever!” © compares physical and psychological scares, mentioning that “psychological wounds are not so gloriously presented” If I can borrow from him, Psychological wounds are not gloriously presented, but they should be. They are after all part of my, our life. The Vietnam experience made me who I am today. Those psychological scares need to be processed and the experiences that caused them shared with others.<br><br>
In Vietnam we responded to a situation and observed the immediate results of our actions, the scares we carry from those experiences have unfortunately laid for the most part dormant in our hearts and minds. They have remained there silent, still and unprocessed. <br><br>
But all those psychological scares were necessary to protect us in battle, but today they long to be released they are experiences which our nation never allowed us to share.  So we find, both the good and the bad remaining in limbo, just there at the surface. <br><br>
Healing, we need to realize can not come while our Vietnam services are covered with undeserved shame.  That is not what war is all about, that is not why we went to battle. That is not a burden we were required to carry for our country. The oath I took to protect our country from all enemies foreign and domestic did not require for me to ascribe to undeserved shame.<br><br>
We have meanwhile tried to pacify those unprocessed, unshared experiences with time, with a broken spirit we have sometimes shared those experiences silently with a loved ones that did not understand. But its those times and experiences that have made us what we are today. <br><br>
Its only when others that have experienced what we have, who share their experiences with us that we find the encouragement to move forward. To embrace what we did and to be proud of what we accomplished. They are that tangible point of reference needed for us to be able to move out. You Paul have discovered it and that is good. <br><br>
Those experiences are not all negative; they reflect the honor, and bravery, the respect and friendship we once shared. They are the essence of what made this country great and what can still be found in the hearts, in the minds and in the souls of the Vietnam veteran.  Boy, does this nation desperately needs those type of experiences and heroes. <br><br>
You, Paul are that type of American servicemen. You served with honor and deserve the respect this country never gave you. This country laid upon us a heavy guilt trip which we didn’t deserve but we like obedient soldiers have silently endured that pain all these years. <br><br>
Its time for us to use those experiences for the good and for the individual those experiences turned us into. I am today what I am because of Vietnam. I hold my head up high, proud of my service in Vietnam, I owe it to myself, my God, my family and those who gave their lives that I may live to do so.<br><br>
Paul once again you have brought us to deep reflection, thank you<br><br>
Your brother in Peace and in War,<br><br>
Sparrowhawk<br><br>
 Now did I ever tell you about the Army paratrooper that came into the Marine bar in DaNang with his parachute still attached…………<br>

